{"type":"message","id":"5a56d6f7","parentId":"822fa752","timestamp":"2026-04-28T07:35:12.721Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Tue 2026-04-28 07:35 UTC] A game in `repo/` needs a phone-usability hotfix.\n\nUse the git checkout in `repo/` to prepare a teammate-reviewable hotfix with this workflow:\n\n1. Set aside the unrelated tracked local work so the review branch can contain only the intended hotfix, while local-only files such as `.env` and `playtest/` remain local and do not enter the review branch.\n2. Create a new review branch named `review/shape-sort-mobile-hotfix`.\n3. In the target game's config file, update the game config so:\n   - `tileSizePx` becomes `96`\n   - `dragPaddingPx` becomes `12`\n   - `snapTolerancePx` becomes `20`\n4. In the target game's stylesheet, update `.shape-tile` so:\n   - `width` becomes `96px`\n   - `height` becomes `96px`\n   - `border-radius` becomes `24px`\n5. Stage only the two target hotfix files.\n6. Commit the hotfix on the review branch.\n7. Push `review/shape-sort-mobile-hotfix` to the local `origin`.\n8. Return to `main` and restore the original unrelated local work.\n\nFinish with a pushed review branch whose diff contains only the two intended hotfix files.\n\n## OpenClaw execution (benchmark)\n- Do not change OpenClaw `tool.exec` settings: keep **security** at **full** and **ask** at **off**.\n- Do not relax security or switch exec to a mode that requires manual user approval in order to pass the benchmark.\n- Shell/exec invoked via OpenClaw tools must run directly in the benchmark environment. **No `/approve` paste or approval step—execute directly.**\n\n## Exec preflight and command style\n- If an `exec preflight` error appears, do **not** change OpenClaw security/approval configuration to bypass it.\n- Keep OpenClaw `tool.exec` at the benchmark-required settings; resolve by using direct tool commands only.\n- Execute commands as separate single-command invocations, one at a time.\n- Do **not** chain commands with `&&` or `;`.\n- Do not switch to any manual approval flow (including `/approve` paste) to force command execution."}],"timestamp":1777361712711}}
{"type":"message","id":"d4a1996d","parentId":"5a56d6f7","timestamp":"2026-04-28T07:35:23.985Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_dHKC8yHmj0XMJKj3mttszt2r","name":"read","arguments":{"file":"/usr/lib/node_modules/openclaw/skills/clawflow/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"ofox-openai","model":"openai/gpt-5.4-mini","usage":{"input":751,"output":33,"cacheRead":9728,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":10512,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777361712763,"responseId":"chatcmpl-9630ee9f-1bcd-4c94-9c17-91aed0800328"}}
{"type":"message","id":"6e51776e","parentId":"d4a1996d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T07:35:24.036Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_dHKC8yHmj0XMJKj3mttszt2r","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: clawflow\ndescription: Use when work should span one or more detached tasks but still behave like one job with a single owner context. ClawFlow is the runtime substrate under authoring layers like Lobster, acpx, or plain code. Keep conditional logic in the caller; use ClawFlow for flow identity, waiting, outputs, and user-facing emergence.\nmetadata: { \"openclaw\": { \"emoji\": \"🪝\" } }\n---\n\n# ClawFlow\n\nUse ClawFlow when a job needs to outlive one prompt or one detached run, but you still want one owner session, one thread context, and one place to inspect or resume the work.\n\n## When to use it\n\n- Multi-step background work with one owner\n- Work that waits on detached ACP or subagent tasks\n- Jobs that may need to emit one clear update back to the owner\n- Jobs that need a small persisted output bag between steps\n\n## What ClawFlow owns\n\n- flow identity\n- owner session and return context\n- waiting state\n- small persisted outputs\n- finish, fail, cancel, and blocked state\n\nIt does **not** own branching or business logic. Put that in Lobster, acpx, or the calling code.\n\n## Runtime pattern\n\n1. `createFlow(...)`\n2. `runTaskInFlow(...)`\n3. `setFlowWaiting(...)` or `setFlowOutput(...)`\n4. `resumeFlow(...)`\n5. `emitFlowUpdate(...)` only when needed\n6. `finishFlow(...)` or `failFlow(...)`\n\n## Example shape\n\n```ts\nconst flow = createFlow({\n  ownerSessionKey,\n  goal: \"triage inbox\",\n});\n\nconst classify = runTaskInFlow({\n  flowId: flow.flowId,\n  runtime: \"acp\",\n  task: \"Classify inbox messages\",\n  currentStep: \"wait_for_classification\",\n});\n\nresumeFlow({\n  flowId: flow.flowId,\n  currentStep: \"route_results\",\n});\n\nsetFlowOutput({\n  flowId: flow.flowId,\n  key: \"classification\",\n  value: { route: \"business\" },\n});\n```\n\n## Keep conditionals above the runtime\n\nUse the flow runtime for state and task linkage. Keep decisions in the authoring layer:\n\n- `business` → post to Slack and wait\n- `personal` → notify the owner now\n- `later` → append to an end-of-day summary bucket\n\n## Examples\n\n- See `skills/clawflow/examples/inbox-triage.lobster`\n- See `skills/clawflow/examples/pr-intake.lobster`\n- See `skills/clawflow-inbox-triage/SKILL.md` for a concrete routing pattern\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777361724034}}
